In this case, you could use the "text", "followers", "following", and "favorite_count" columns as features. You would need to preprocess the "text" column to convert it into a numerical format, such as using a bag-of-words or TF-IDF approach.

# Once you have selected your features, you can use a library such as scikit-learn to perform DBSCAN. You would first need to standardize your features using a scaler such as StandardScaler. Then, you can fit the DBSCAN model to your data, specifying the epsilon and minimum_samples hyperparameters.

# The output of DBSCAN is a clustering of the data points into different clusters, as well as a set of points that are considered to be noise. Points that belong to the same cluster are considered to be similar to each other based on their feature values.

# In the context of this dataset, running DBSCAN could potentially help identify groups of tweets that are similar to each other based on the content of the tweet as well as the number of followers, following, and favorite count of the user who tweeted it. This could be useful for tasks such as identifying popular topics or trends on social media, or for detecting clusters of bots or spam accounts.

In [138]:
from collections import Counter

def make_bow(text, vocab):
    vocab_set = set(vocab)
    bow = []
    for doc in text:
        token_counts = Counter(doc.split())
        bow_doc = [int(token in vocab_set and token_counts[token] > 0) for token in vocab]
        bow.append(bow_doc)
    return bow
bow = make_bow(text, vocab)

wcss = [] ### for storing wcss number

real_news_df = real_news_df.dropna()

X_real = real_news_df[['followers', 'statuses_count']]
X_real

## your code goes here
for i in range(1, 11):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=i, init='k-means++', random_state=0, max_iter=300, n_init=10).fit(X_real)
    wcss.append(kmeans.inertia_)


xaxis = [i for i in range(1, 11)]
plt.plot(xaxis, wcss)
plt.title('The Elbow Method')
plt.ylabel('WCSS')
plt.xlabel('Number of clusters')

# initialize the DBSCAN algorithm
dbscan = DBSCAN(eps=5000, min_samples=100, metric='euclidean')

# fit the algorithm to the data
dbscan.fit(X_real)

# get the cluster labels
labels = dbscan.labels_
uniquelab = np.unique(labels)

# add the labels to the dataset
real_news_df['dbscan_label'] = labels

sns.scatterplot(x= X_real["followers"], y = X_real["statuses_count"], s = 25, hue=labels, palette = sns.color_palette("colorblind", len(uniquelab)))
